Load the raw data¶

  1. clusterQuality = good/mua are considered as a single class (1); noise is another class (0)
  2. clusterWaveforms = waveforms from peak channel number - 16 to peak channel + 16. Length of waveform=82

Considerations:¶

  1. Allen Institute uses 61 length waveform (removes first 21 index values)
  2. Currently we are selecting waveforms according to just channel number. Some of the selected channels might not be in spatial proximity. Any suggestions?

Build the cnn model¶

In [12]:
def build_cnn_model(activation, input_shape):
    model = Sequential()
    
    # 2 Convolution layer with Max pooling
    model.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(15, 15),activation='relu',
                     padding='same',input_shape=input_shape))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding='same'))
    #model.add(Dropout(0.4))
    model.add(Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(7, 7),activation='relu',
                     padding='same',input_shape=input_shape))
    model.add(BatchNormalization(momentum=0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding='same'))
    #model.add(Dropout(0.4))
    model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization(momentum=0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding='same'))
    #model.add(Dropout(0.4))
    model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization(momentum=0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(4, 4), padding='same'))
    #model.add(Dropout(0.4))
    model.add(Flatten())
    
    # 3 Full connected layer
    model.add(Dense(16, activation = activation, kernel_regularizer='l1_l2'))
    model.add(Dense(8, activation = activation, kernel_regularizer='l1_l2'))
    model.add(Dense(2, activation = 'softmax')) # 2 classes
    
    # summarize the model
    tf.keras.utils.plot_model(model, to_file='modelWf.png', show_shapes=True)
    print(model.summary())

    return model

Batch normalization makes the training more efficient at the same time by reducing the covariance shift within internal layers (change in the distribution of network activations due to the change in network parameters during training) during training and with the advantages of working with batches.

In [13]:
# compile the model
def compile_and_fit_model(model, datagen_, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, batch_size, n_epochs):
    model.compile(optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(),loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['sparse_categorical_accuracy'])  
    # fit the model
    history = model.fit_generator(datagen_.flow(X_train, y_train,batch_size),
                        epochs=n_epochs, verbose=1,validation_data=(X_test, y_test))
    return model, history
